Lessons that can be learned today from the Cuban Missile Crisis
"Thirteen Days" ("Dreizehn Tage"), a new film about the Cuban Missile Crisis, will soon be released in theaters across many countries.
Everyone should watch this film, not only because it deals with the past, but also because it offers insights into current events – particularly regarding the controversies surrounding a U.S. national missile defense system and the various regional discussions in India and Pakistan, Taiwan and China, North and South Korea, which could one day escalate into a nuclear conflict.
On October 16, 1962, President John F. Kennedy called his closest advisors together in the White House.
Aerial photographs of the area had revealed the construction of a nuclear weapons site on Cuba.
The decisions made during the following thirteen days, and the decisions that could not be made, could have led to the outbreak of a nuclear war.
The film illustrates what happened in the White House during those days.
Sound recordings made during Kennedy's presidency played a significant role in the creation of the film.
After the film's premiere in America, the Kennedy School of Government at Harvard organized a discussion panel that was meant to discuss the film as well as the crisis it deals with.
Participants in this panel included, among others: Robert McNamara, Defense Secretary under President Kennedy; Theodore Sorensen, a close advisor and speechwriter for Kennedy; Ernest R. May, a history professor at Harvard who wrote a book about the "Kennedy Tapes"; and finally Graham Allison, a political science professor at Harvard who presented a classic study on the Cuban Missile Crisis, the work "Essence of Decision," 30 years ago.
Moreover, Peter A. Almond, the film's producer, was present.
Although the film's handling of the subject was criticized in several points, the panel participants were able to agree that the film accurately portrays the problems and pressure that President Kennedy faced.
What conclusions can be drawn today from the Cuban Missile Crisis?
Theodore Sorensen summarized them as follows:
· Advisors must play their role in a crisis, but it is exclusively the president who ultimately bears the responsibility.
The majority of Kennedy's advisors – both civilian and military – wanted to attack Cuba at that time.
Only through Kennedy's sober analysis and his probing questions could alternatives and dangers be identified that were essential in determining the consequences.
· It is necessary to understand how an opponent thinks; in addition, communication channels must remain open.
Cornering an opponent without keeping diplomatic channels open that allow you to understand the opponent's situation could prove disastrous.
· The United States is dependent on allies.
Kennedy acted this way because the NATO, other allies, and world opinion supported him.
· A certain amount of time is needed to make good decisions.
When it comes to life or death, a politician cannot allow the media to push him into an action.
The fact that a week passed, during which all involved factors were meticulously examined and weighed, was crucial for the outcome.
But would such a time frame for deliberation even exist today, given the current mass media?
Robert McNamara emphasized that it was necessary to put oneself in the opponent's position.
In one of the much-critiqued scenes of the film, McNamara explains to a war-hungry admiral that the naval blockade that Kennedy imposed on Cuba was primarily intended to send a signal to Chairman Khrushchev about Kennedy's intention, and was not meant as a means to stop certain Soviet ships.
Could Kennedy have acted even more calmly?
After all, the USA had also stationed nuclear warheads near the USSR.
Khrushchev's decision to station missiles in Cuba merely reflected this policy.
Yet Kennedy was anxious about the consequences that the stationing of Soviet missiles in Cuba would have for Berlin.
The pressure of nuclear weapons in Cuba would have made the defense of Berlin even more difficult, which was part of Khrushchev's strategy.
"Ultimately, the Berlin Crisis was resolved by the outcomes of the Cuban Missile Crisis," claimed historian Ernest May.
"Soon it will be too late," was a widely circulated argument that Kennedy heard from his advisors.
The advisors wanted to attack Cuba while the missiles – as they assumed – were en route to Cuba by sea.
A US force of about 180,000 men was prepared for an invasion; there were even plans for a blitz bombing campaign that would have been larger in scale than the NATO attack in Kosovo sixty years later. "It took me thirty years," said McNamara, "to find out that there were already atomic weapons on Cuba: 162 warheads, and 90 of them were strategic nuclear warheads."
McNamara received this information occasioned by a meeting with Fidel Castro.
He posed the following three questions to Castro: 1) Did you know about it?
2) If so, what did you recommend?
3) What would have been the consequences for Cuba?
Castro replied: "I knew what was going on.
And I explicitly recommended that atomic weapons be used.
I knew that this would have led to the annihilation of Cuba."
Castro and – to a greater extent – his comrade Che Guevara were ready to let Cuba go up in smoke, so that their country would become a martyr in the struggle for the world revolution!
An invasion would thus have resulted in the death of 80 million Americans and the destruction of Cuba, simply because the Kennedy government lacked sufficient knowledge of the facts (a situation that often occurs when a politician has to make a decision alone).
McNamara is firmly convinced that an invasion would "undoubtedly" have led to a Soviet atomic attack against the USA.
Chruschtschow's control over the Soviet military in Cuba was indeed limited: U2 planes flying over Cuban airspace were shot down despite explicit instructions to the contrary from the chairman.
A difficult question that did not arise during this debate at Harvard is the following: What would have happened if the opponent had not been Chruschtschow, who distinguished himself during the crisis by more rational behavior, but rather an adversary of the type of Saddam Hussein, Kim Jong Il, or a fundamentalist?
Given the proliferation of atomic weapons, this danger could one day become a reality.
Today's discussions about limited missile defense and the threat of atomic blackmail by rogue states should be conducted in the light of this terrible but quite realistic thought.
Harvard has launched a new website where essential documents about the Cuban Missile Crisis and current nuclear threats can be found: www.cubanmissilecrisis.org .
